{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3373f65e-b3f9-4dc5-bcf2-cc49d97e501e","content":"Your project isn't in the current directory, but here's how to configure it. Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"${workspaceFolder}/src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`dotnet run --project`** — launches your server; adjust the path if needed.\n- Your server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, configure it with `.WithStdioServerTransport()`.\n- VS Code will auto-discover the file and prompt you to start the server.\n\nIf you prefer **user-level** config (all workspaces), add it to VS Code's `settings.json` under `\"mcp\"` instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"00d4384c-726d-48aa-a050-d6a8b4def85c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user says they built it. They're just asking how to configure mcp.json. I can answer this directly.","outputTokens":319,"requestId":"B030:2DB26F:D4A34D:F14354:6A027D3C"},"id":"5fd98d62-d76b-40cf-ae67-2cb865e4882d","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:07:17.646Z","parentId":"680acefe-db7b-4b34-b8f3-f66a835fbb27"}
